{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"749168d4-f094-42b7-912a-1b1293c06222","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### In your `.csproj`, add these properties:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>  <!-- CLI command name -->\n  <PackageOutputType>Exe</PackageOutputType>\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/you/repo</RepositoryUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points:\n\n1. **`PackAsTool = true`** — this is the critical property that makes it installable via `dotnet tool install`\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the command users will run (e.g., `my-mcp-server`)\n3. **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — dotnet tools must be console apps\n4. Your `Program.cs` should use **stdio transport** (which you already have)\n\n### Build & publish:\n\n```bash\ndotnet pack -c Release\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_NUGET_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server  # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's all the configuration needed — `PackAsTool` does the heavy lifting. Want me to scaffold the project?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"517d7012-de01-4a00-9a64-c5370b86382c","outputTokens":477,"requestId":"C01D:282C31:1C858DB:201E563:6A07C20B"},"id":"cea2843b-58dd-4cf7-93a6-805d54da7604","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:02:12.726Z","parentId":"ab2c5cd3-c54c-4abe-b089-268f3af1d041"}
